(23, 7, 'industry-open-day', 'Industry Open Day', '<p><font style="background-color: #000000" color="#ffffff" face="Arial"><span class="whiteheader">INDUSTRY OPEN DAY</span></font></p>\n<hr size="2" width="100%" />\n<p><font style="background-color: #000000" color="#ffffff" face="Arial"><span class="uppercase">The Palace George Cinemas<br />\nSaturday 29 May, 12PM – 4PM<br />\n</span></font></p>\n<p><font style="background-color: #000000" color="#ffffff" face="Arial"><span class="uppercase">FREE ALL AGES EVENT</span></font></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><font style="background-color: #000000" color="#ffffff" face="Arial"><img alt="" src="/Uploads/IOD.jpg" width="378" height="200" /><br />\n</font></p>\n<p><font style="background-color: #000000" color="#ffffff" face="Arial"></font></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><font style="background-color: #000000" color="#ffffff" face="Arial">People who are making films, thinking about making films or want to know how films are made should come along to the 2010 Industry Open Day.</font></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><font style="background-color: #000000" color="#ffffff" face="Arial">Check out Paul Harris presenting his famous Triple R Broadcasters radio program <em>Film Buffs Forecast</em> and come armed with questions for our post production houses, film schools, funding bodies, film distributors and industry associations.</font></p>\n<p><font style="background-color: #000000" color="#ffffff" face="Arial"><br />\n&nbsp;</font></p>\n<p><span class="uppercase"><font style="background-color: #000000" color="#ffffff" face="Arial">Stall holders on the day will include:</font></span></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><font style="background-color: #000000" color="#ffffff" face="Arial">Australian Directors Guild<br />\nAustralian Film Television &amp; Radio School (AFTRS)<br />\nAustralian Screen Editors Guild<br />\nAustralian Writers Guild<br />\nBlue SKYS Media<br />\nDeakin University<br />\nHolmesglen Institute<br />\nMusic &amp; Effects<br />\nNational Film &amp; Sound Archive (NFSA)<br />\nOpen Channel<br />\nProfile Creative<br />\nRMIT University<br />\nScreen Hub<br />\nScreen Producers Association<br />\nof Australia (SPAA)<br />\nScreen Rights<br />\nShort Attention<br />\nSwinburne University<br />\nSt Kilda Film Festival<br />\ninternational guests<br />\nFilm and Television, Faculty of the VCA and Music, The University of Melbourne<br />\nVictoria University<br />\n</font></p>\n<p><font style="background-color: #000000" color="#ffffff" face="Arial">and more…</font><br />\n&nbsp;</p>\n', '2010-04-28 15:38:30', '2010-05-12 14:36:23'),
(24, 1, 'welcome', 'Welcome', '<p class="whiteheader">WELCOME TO THE 27TH ST KILDA FILM FESTIVAL<br />\n</p>\n<hr size="2" width="100%" />\n<p>Congratulations to the organisers of the St Kilda Film Festival for creating such an interesting and exciting program in 2010.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\nEach year the Festival organisers offer a very wide range of exciting films that provide Australian audiences with entertaining, moving and thought provoking Australian stories. The last 12 months have been an especially exciting time for Australian film. In 2009 we saw the highest number of Australian films released in 25 years and above average box office earnings. This is excellent news for our film sector, economy and the wider community. We are seeing more stories in cinemas and on television that reflect the Australian experience.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\nInternationally, our films have been well-received with many Australian films screening at prestigious international film festivals including Bran Nue Dae at the Berlin International Film Festival, Animal Kingdom at the Sundance Film Festival and Samson and Delilah at Cannes and the International Film Festival Rotterdam.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\nI am extremely pleased to see that the strong performance of the screen industry continues in 2010 and I congratulate everyone at the St Kilda Film Festival for their role in promoting Australia’s film sector success.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><img alt="" src="/Uploads/Peter Garrett.jpg" height="147" width="147" /></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<span class="uppercase">Peter Garrett MP<br />\nMinister for Environment Protection,<br />\nHeritage and the Arts</span><br />\n<hr size="2" width="100%" />\n<br />\n<p>\nThe Victorian Government is proud to sponsor the St Kilda Film Festival, a fantastic celebration and acknowledgment of the best and brightest short films and filmmakers. Film Victoria has supported the St Kilda Film Festival since its inception 27 years ago, and recognises its important and enduring role in promoting the local screen industry.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\nThe St Kilda Film Festival screens more Australian short films than any other festival in Australia. Recognised as the country’s premier short film festival, it is a fantastic vehicle for budding Victorian talent to showcase their projects.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\nEvery year, Festival audiences range from established filmmakers and passionate film buffs to a general audience of eager newcomers, curious spectators and people who simply enjoy good film, offering new filmmakers broad exposure to a diverse audience.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\nI wish all competing filmmakers the best of luck with their screenings. There is an incredible array of talent on display this year, and I encourage audiences to get along to as many films as they can. I’d also like to extend my thanks to the City of Port Phillip and the Festival staff. Putting together such an amazing festival can’t be easy, but they do it every year and they do a fantastic job.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><img alt="" src="/Uploads/Gavin Jennings.jpg" height="147" width="147" /></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<span class="uppercase">Gavin Jennings MLC<br />\nMinister for Innovation</span><br />\n<hr size="2" width="100%" />\n<br />\n<p>\nWelcome to the 27th St Kilda Film Festival, the longest running short film festival in Australia. It all began back in 1984, when the film program at St Kilda Festival became so popular it turned into an event in its own right. Since then, it has grown into the six day extravaganza that we all know and love. The Festival supports the Australian film industry and its practitioners. It also gives Australian filmmakers the opportunity to have their work screened to as a wide an audience as possible. Along with a fantastic Festival program, we are proud to present two programs for and by young people, Armed &amp; Dangerous and Under the Radar.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\nIt’s impossible to name all of our sponsors and partners, but I would like to make special mention of our government partners; Film Victoria and Screen Australia. I’d also like to thank Movie Network Channels, our major sponsor — without our sponsors and partners the Festival would not be possible.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\nAfter its Melbourne run, we are taking the Film Festival on an Australian tour visiting capital cities as well as regional destinations in all states and territories. It’s a great way for us to show our support for the filmmakers that are participating in this year’s event. I am also pleased to be giving the local community the chance to see some of the best Australian filmmaking talent going. </p>\n<p>Enjoy!</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;<img src="/Uploads/Frank OConnor.jpeg" alt="" height="147" width="147" border="0" /></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><span class="uppercase">Cr Frank O’Connor</span></p>\n<span class="uppercase">\nMayor, City of Port Phillip</span><br />\n<hr size="2" width="100%" />\n<br />\nShort films are experiencing a renaissance of startling proportions. Films can be easily accessed now on social media like mobile phones, the internet and YouTube, reaching international audiences. However there is a downside, it’s a solitary viewing experience and an inadequate substitute for a much more effective viewing platform — a darkened auditorium full of eager punters and the excited buzz in the foyer that follows each screening. St Kilda Film Festival, Australia’s longest running and largest competitive short film event operates a national competition which we are justifiably proud of. This is achieved while maintaining strong roots within the local community, making St Kilda a roots-oriented, community event.<br />\n<p>\n</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>The Festival provides a unique platform for emerging filmmakers to showcase their craft skills and creativity. Those shorts which made it through to this year’s 100 are notable for their innovation and originality.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\nIt’s a privilege and a pleasure to promote such films.<br />\n<br />\n<p>\nSee you there!</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><span class="uppercase"><img alt="" src="/Uploads/Paul Harris.jpg" height="147" width="147" /></span></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><span class="uppercase">\nPaul Harris</span></p>\n<span class="uppercase">\nFestival Director</span><br />\n<hr size="2" width="100%" />\n<br />\n<p>\nA film festival is only ever as good as the films within it. Thanks to the overwhelming talent of Australian filmmakers, the 2010 St Kilda Film Festival is shaping up to be one of the best yet.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\nThe films on show this year showcase the gamut of local filmmaking talent and range from comedy to horror, documentary to animation and everything in between. In every film there are characters we recognise, cities and towns we know and cultures that we are all a part of. It is an honour to be able to screen these stories.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\nWhile there’s more Australian short films in this Festival than you could hope to see in a week, there’s also plenty of other events inside this jam packed six day program. SoundKILDA returns to celebrate Australian music videos, and our international short film series explores films from all over the globe. The forum series and Industry Open Day bring industry experts together so you can get all the support you need for your own work, and you may just find your next cast, crew or film-loving friend in the Festival Club. A big thanks to everyone involved in this Festival and particularly the dedicated staff and volunteers who put it together with a lot of blood, sweat and tears.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>From the 25th to the 30th May St Kilda will be filled with everything you love about Australian film. Make sure you’re a part of it.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;<img alt="" src="/Uploads/Adele Denison.jpg" height="147" width="147" /></p>\n<span class="uppercase">\n</span>\n<p><span class="uppercase">\n</span></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p class="uppercase">Adele Denison</p>\n<p class="uppercase">Festival Producer</p>\n<span class="uppercase">\n</span>\n<p><br />\n</p>\n<hr size="2" width="100%" />\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n', '2010-04-29 17:20:16', '2010-05-06 12:29:31'),
(73, 13, 'frequently-asked-questions', 'Frequently Asked Questions', '<style type="text/css">@import url(http://www.stkildafilmfestival.com.au/callforentries/css/template.css);</style>\n<style type="text/css">@import url(http://www.stkildafilmfestival.com.au/callforentries/css/template.css);</style>\n<style type="text/css">@import url(http://www.stkildafilmfestival.com.au/callforentries/css/template.css);</style>\n<style type="text/css">@import url(http://www.stkildafilmfestival.com.au/callforentries/css/template.css);</style>\n<style type="text/css">@import url(http://www.stkildafilmfestival.com.au/callforentries/css/template.css);</style>\n<style type="text/css">@import url(http://www.stkildafilmfestival.com.au/callforentries/css/template.css);</style>\n<p><span class="whiteheader">FR</span><span class="whiteheader">EQUENTLY ASKED QUESTIONS</span><span class="whiteheader"> </span></p>\n<hr />\n<p><span class="uppercase"><span style="color: #ffffff"><span class="uppercase"><a style="color: #ffffff" href="#n1"><strong>What films are eligible for the St Kilda Film Festival competition?&nbsp;</strong></a></span></span></span>&nbsp; </p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><span class="uppercase"><a href="#n2"><strong>What length of film may be submitted?</strong></a></span></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><span class="uppercase"><a href="#n3"><strong>Can I submit a work in progress?</strong></a></span></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><span class="uppercase"><a href="#n4"><strong>What material should I submit?</strong></a></span></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><span class="uppercase"><a href="#n5"><strong>Where do I send my entry?</strong></a></span></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><span class="uppercase"><a href="#n6"><strong>What is the entry fee?</strong></a></span></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><span class="uppercase"><a href="#n7"><strong>What formats can be screened at the Festival?</strong></a></span></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><span class="uppercase"><a href="#n8"><strong>When will selection be confirmed?</strong></a></span></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><span class="uppercase"><a href="#n9"><strong>How will my material be returned?</strong></a></span></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><span class="uppercase"><a href="#n10"><strong>How do I contact the Festival Office?</strong></a></span><br />\n<br />\n<br />\n<span class="uppercase"><a name="n1"><strong>&#183; What films are eligible for the St Kilda Film Festival competition?</strong></a><strong><br />\n</strong></span>Only Australian entries are eligible for the St Kilda Film Festival competition. International entries will not be accepted for competition. St Kilda Film Festival is open to all film genres.<br />\nIf you are unsure if your film is eligible, please call Festival staff on 03 9209 6490 or email <a href="&#109;&#97;&#105;&#108;&#116;&#111;&#58;&#102;&#105;&#108;&#109;&#102;&#101;&#115;&#116;&#64;&#112;&#111;&#114;&#116;&#112;&#104;&#105;&#108;&#108;&#105;&#112;&#46;&#118;&#105;&#99;&#46;&#103;&#111;&#118;&#46;&#97;&#117;"><span style="color: #ffffff"><span style="color: #ffffff">filmfest@portphillip.vic.gov.au</span></span></a></p>\n<p><br />\n<span class="uppercase"><a name="n2"><strong>&#183; What length of film may be submitted?</strong></a></span><br />\nDue to scheduling considerations films with a running time of more than 40 minutes may have some restrictions placed upon them. Filmmakers with longer films are advised to contact Festival staff for further information before submitting their entries.</p>\n<p><br />\n<span class="uppercase"><a name="n3"><strong>&#183; Can I submit a work in progress?</strong></a></span><br />\nWorks in progress may be entered. Indicate work in progress status clearly on the preview tape and advise of expected completion date.</p>\n<p><br />\n<span class="uppercase"><a name="n4"><strong>&#183; What material should I submit?</strong></a></span><br />\n1 Entry form completed and submitted<br />\n2 Payment completed via online service, or by cheque or money order sent with preview tape.<br />\n3 Preview copy of film on DVD (please ensure DVD is not copy-protected, as multiple copies may need to be made for judging).<br />\n4 One film still to be used in the program/website if film is successful.<br />\n<br />\nStills must be submitted on a CD. Please ensure resolution is at least 300 DPI and as large as possible. Do not email your stills – the large files block up our inbox! Materials that are emailed will not be accepted.<br />\n</p>\n<p><br />\n</p>\n<p>If your film is selected for inclusion in the Festival you will be required to provide your film in either 35mm, 16mm, Digibeta, HD Cam, or Blu-Ray only. The Festival is unable to screen SP Betacam.</p>\nOPTIONAL MATERIAL:<br />\n- CV of the writer/director/producer<br />\n- Publicity material (ie reviews, press kits etc)\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><br />\n<span class="uppercase"><a name="n5"><strong>&#183; Where do I send my entry?</strong></a></span><br />\nOnce the online entry form and payment have been completed, preview tapes and additional material should be posted to:<br />\n<br />\nSt Kilda Film Festival<br />\nPrivate Bag No 3<br />\nPO St Kilda <br />\nVIC 3182<br />\n<br />\nOr delivered by hand to:<br />\nSt Kilda Film Festival<br />\nLevel 1<br />\n232 Carlisle Street<br />\nBalaclava<br />\nVIC 3183<br />\nEntries MUST be postmarked or&nbsp;received by 5pm, January&nbsp;31 2012.</p>\n<p><br />\n<span class="uppercase"><a name="n6"><strong>&#183; What is the entry fee?</strong></a></span><br />\nFor Individuals:<br />\n$33.00 including GST applies to each film submitted.<br />\nSchools and Institutions:<br />\n$132.00 including GST for a compilation of up to 10 films.<br />\nThe entry fee can be paid online once an entry form has been receipted, or by cheque or money order sent to the Festival office. Fees are non-refundable.</p>\n<p><br />\n<span class="uppercase"><a name="n7"><strong>&#183; What formats can be screened at the Festival?</strong></a></span><br />\nSt Kilda Film Festival will only screen productions finished on 35mm, 16mm, Digibeta, HDCAM and Blu-Ray only. The Festival is unable to screen SP Betacam.<br />\nTo ensure your film is screened correctly, you must include screening gauge and ratio details as requested on the entry form. <a href="http://www.stkildafilmfestival.com.au/callforentries/page-79" target="_blank"><span style="color: #ffffff"><a href="http://www.stkildafilmfestival.com.au/callforentries/page-79" target="_blank">CLICK HERE for more information on accepted screening formats and audio specifications</a>.</span></a></p>\n<p><br />\n<span class="uppercase"><a name="n8"><strong>&#183; When will selection be confirmed?</strong></a></span><br />\nIf your film is selected for the competition you will be sent a letter of confirmation by 2nd April 2012. Film Prints or tape masters must be received by 20th April 2012.</p>\n<p><br />\n<span class="uppercase"><strong><span class="uppercase"><strong>&#183; </strong></span><a name="n9">How will my screening copy be returned?</a></strong></span><br />\nScreening copies will be sent to the nominated return address as stipulated on your entry form. Please make sure you update your address with the Festival Office if it changes.</p>\n<p><br />\n<span class="uppercase"><a name="n10"><strong>&#183; How do I contact the Festival Office?</strong></a></span><br />\nBy phone on 03 9209 6490, or email at filmfest@portphillip.vic.gov.au<br />\n</p>\n', '2010-09-29 09:37:56', '2012-02-21 09:32:10'),
(74, 13, 'terms-conditions', 'Terms & Conditions', '<style type="text/css">@import url(http://www.stkildafilmfestival.com.au/callforentries/css/template.css);</style>\n<style type="text/css">@import url(http://www.stkildafilmfestival.com.au/callforentries/css/template.css);</style>\n<style type="text/css">@import url(http://www.stkildafilmfestival.com.au/callforentries/css/template.css);</style>\n<style type="text/css">@import url(http://www.stkildafilmfestival.com.au/callforentries/css/template.css);</style>\n<p><span class="whiteheader">terms &amp; conditions</span><span class="whiteheader"> </span></p>\n<hr />\n<p>&nbsp;<br />\n<strong>1.</strong> Only Australian entries are eligible for the St Kilda Film Festival competition.<br />\nSt Kilda Film Festival is open to all film genres. <br />\nIf you are unsure of eligibility, please contact the Festival office on 03 9209 6490 or email <a href="&#109;&#97;&#105;&#108;&#116;&#111;&#58;&#102;&#105;&#108;&#109;&#102;&#101;&#115;&#116;&#64;&#112;&#111;&#114;&#116;&#112;&#104;&#105;&#108;&#108;&#105;&#112;&#46;&#118;&#105;&#99;&#46;&#103;&#111;&#118;&#46;&#97;&#117;"><span style="color: #ffffff"><span style="color: #ffffff">filmfest@portphillip.vic.gov.au</span></span></a></p>\n<p><br />\n<strong>2.</strong> The producer grants the St Kilda Film Festival the rights to:<br />\n(a) Exhibit the film in the St Kilda Film Festival and any subsequent tour<br />\n(b) Reproduce the film for inclusion as part of a compilation<br />\n(c) Exhibit the production either in part or in total for promotional purposes</p>\n<p><br />\n<strong>3.</strong> The producer warrants to the St Kilda Film Festival that they have obtained all the necessary permissions to enter this film and that the film does not infringe the rights, including copyright, of any third party. This includes use of music and literary (ie if your film is based on a novel or poem).</p>\n<p><br />\n<strong>4.</strong> Entries will not be considered valid until the entry fee has been paid</p>\n<p><br />\n<strong>5.</strong> Entries must be received or postmarked by 5pm,&nbsp;Tuesday 31&nbsp;January 2012</p>\n<p><br />\n<strong>6.</strong> Entries may not be withdrawn after 26th March 2012</p>\n<p><br />\n<strong>7.</strong> If your film is selected for the competition you will be sent a letter of confirmation by 2nd April 2012. Film Prints, or tape masters must be received by 20th April 2012.</p>\n<p><br />\n<strong>8.</strong> Materials submitted in the initial entry process will not be returned. Screening copies of films selected to screen in the Top 100 will be returned to the nominated address on the entry form after the Festival. Please make sure this address is correct and if any details change please email us at <a style="color: #ffffff" href="&#109;&#97;&#105;&#108;&#116;&#111;&#58;&#102;&#105;&#108;&#109;&#102;&#101;&#115;&#116;&#64;&#112;&#111;&#114;&#116;&#112;&#104;&#105;&#108;&#108;&#105;&#112;&#46;&#118;&#105;&#99;&#46;&#103;&#111;&#118;&#46;&#97;&#117;">filmfest@portphillip.vic.gov.au</a></p>\n<p><br />\n<strong>9.</strong> The St Kilda Film Festival will pay for the return of participating films for the Festival within Australia. Forwarding of prints to international destinations will be at the filmmaker’s expense. Forwarding films to the Festival is the responsibility of the filmmaker. </p>\n<p><br />\n<strong>10.</strong> Whilst the St Kilda Film Festival will take due care of prints or tapes entered, the Festival will not be responsible for any loss and/or damage to prints, DVDs or tapes while they are in the possession of the Festival or any of the cinemas hosting the Festival or the Tour.</p>\n<p><br />\n<strong>11.</strong> The St Kilda Film Festival will tour a selection of films featured in the Festival in July through to September 2012. All films entered in the St Kilda Film Festival must be available for touring. Tour films will be returned after the tour concludes.</p>\n<p><br />\n<strong>12.</strong> The St Kilda Film Festival will only screen productions finished on 35mm, 16mm, Digibeta, HDCAM&nbsp;and Blu-Ray. We do NOT screen from Beta SP. To ensure your entry is screened correctly, you must include screening gauge and ratio details as requested on the entry form. <a href="http://www.stkildafilmfestival.com.au/callforentries/page-79" target="_blank">CLICK HERE for more information on accepted screening formats and audio specifications</a>.<br />\n</p>\n', '2010-09-29 09:47:24', '2012-01-25 18:10:06'),
