(750, 'Film_title~Where Do Lilacs Come From~Month_completed~December~Year_Completed~2013~Film_running_mins~13~Film_running_seconds~24~where_film__was_made~QLD~Producer~Timothy Ward~Director~Matthew Thorne~Screenwriter~Matthew Thorne~Director_of_Photography~Tennyson Tostee~Production_Designer~Danielle Pearce~Sound_Recordist~Joel Zico~Editor~Dylan Duclos~Composer~Luke Howard~Post_Prod_Sound/Sound_Design~Michael Orenstien~Visual_Effects~Tormod Noreng~Animator~~Other_Key_Crew~~Principal_Cast~Joe Feeny Richard Lund~Genre~Drama/~sypnosis~Where Do Lilacs Come From is a surreal short film told through the eyes of an Alzheimers sufferer as he desperately tries to put together the pieces of his past through the memories of his son.~publicity~I wrote this story in many ways as a response to my memories of losing my Grandmother to Alzheimer’s. Watching my Father endlessly reintroduced his mother to me and my sister was harrowing even to my younger self. Dad would say our visits with Grandma were us ‘saying goodbye in slow-motion’ and ‘to be happy she was still here’. But it all just really stuck with me. Before then I had never seen my Dad scared. Ultimately this story comes from a fear that one day I may stand in his shoes – that I may have to care for the man who has always been my hero like he had to care for Grandma. I have always been fascinated with memory and time and I wanted to experiment with a story where I could blur the lines between reality and imagination in order to take the audience on a journey that could be simultaneously real and unreal - Dementia was the perfect vehicle for this.A Son’s last goodbye to his Father has great personal resonance. I believe every Son fears the day when he must farewell his hero – his Father. And every Father fears the day when they can no longer be a hero to their Son.Screening History:Cast & Crew @ Bond University~is_film_score~Yes~is_student_production~Yes~education_institution~Bond University~this_entry_to_be_a_Victorian_Premiere~Yes~screened_or_broadcast_publicly_in_Australia~No~intend_to_enter_any_other_Australian_film_festivals~Yes~other_Australian_film_festivals_intent_to_enter~Sydney Film Festival ATOM Adelaide Film Festival~by_Aboriginal_filmmakers~No~Principal_first_name~Matthew~Principal_last_name~Thorne~Principal_position~Director~Principal_production_company~~Principal_address~172 Childers Street~Principal_suburb~North Adelaide~Principal_state~SA~Principal_postcode~5006~Telephone_business_hours~0430300433~Telephone_after_hours~0430300433~Principal_mobile~0430300433~Principal_fax~~email_private~matthew.thorne@me.com~email_public~contact@matthewthorne.com.au~Screening_ratio~16:9 Full Height Anamorphic (FHA) *preferred~screening_ratio_other~~Screening_format~Harddrive~Audio_specifications~5.1 Discrete~return_address~172 Childers Street~return_suburb~North Adelaide~return_state~SA~return_postcode~5006~payment_option~credit card~entry_form~shortfilm~', '2014-01-16 23:03:54', '102746'),
