(674, 'Film_title~Cannibal Story~Month_completed~December~Year_Completed~2012~Film_running_mins~6~Film_running_seconds~57~where_film__was_made~WA~Producer~Erin Coates~Director~Sohan Ariel Hayes~Screenwriter~John Carty~Director_of_Photography~~Production_Designer~~Sound_Recordist~~Editor~Sohan Ariel Hayes~Composer~~Post_Prod_Sound/Sound_Design~Roly Skender~Visual_Effects~~Animator~Sohan Ariel Hayes~Other_Key_Crew~~Principal_Cast~Billy Atkins~Genre~Horror/Animation/~sypnosis~Cannibal Story brings to life the dangerous carnivorous beings that live beneath a salt lake in the heart of the Western Desert. This is Martu artist Yunkurra Billy Atkins’ country.~publicity~Kumpupirntily (Lake Disappointment) is the dangerous heart of Martu country in the Western Desert Western Australia – it is a place where cannibal beings live beneath the surface of the salt lake a place where Martu fear to tread. Yunkurra Billy Atkins is the great animator of the dark narratives that score this country and his beguiling paintings have intrigued and challenged art lovers for many years. Now new audiences are invited into the world of his art his imagination and his country as Yunkurra’s paintings are brought to life through a unique collaboration with award-winning animator Sohan Ariel Hayes. Cannibal Story gives sound and motion (and a touch of violence) to the beauty and danger of Yunkurra’s wondrous original paintings.Yunkurra Billy Atkins | ArtistYunkurra is a Martu artist lawman and storyteller. He was born at Well 9 on the Canning Stock Route and grew up in the country around Wiluna but returned north to his traditional country which includes Lake Disappointment Savory Creek and Jilakurru. Yunkurra is a very knowledgeable senior Martu man and an authority on these important Martu places. He narrowly avoided being taken away by missionaries as a child and subsequently grew up with elderly people learning about country in the traditional way. Yunkurra now lives at Jigalong close to his home country. Yunkurra has been painting for longer than other Martu artists and has worked as an independent artist since the early 2000s painting and carving. His work was selected for the 2003 Telstra National Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Art Award and in 2004 he held a solo exhibition of his work at the Courthouse Arts Centre and Gallery in Port Hedland. The National Gallery of Australia has purchased his work and in 2005 he participated in an artists’ exchange program through the Wilin Centre at the Victorian College of the Arts in Melbourne. Sohan Ariel Hayes | Director/AnimatorSohan is a Perth-based media artist working in the fields of expanded and interactive cinema animation pervasive games systems theory locative media. Hayes has exhibited widely including at the Museum of Contemporary Art in Sydney Fremantle Arts Centre the Perth Institute of Contemporary Arts and Goddard de Fiddes Gallery in Perth Plimsoll Gallery in Tasmania the Jerwood Gallery in London TAV Gallery in Taiwan and the Post Museum in Singapore. He has received several national and international awards for his work including from the British Multimedia Industry Awards in 2002 Laval Virtual France (2011) Atom Awards Australia (2002) the Freeplay Independent Game Awards Australia (2010) and in 1997 he received a nomination for ABAF Most Outstanding Patron of the Arts Western Australia.~is_film_score~Yes~is_student_production~No~education_institution~~this_entry_to_be_a_Victorian_Premiere~Yes~screened_or_broadcast_publicly_in_Australia~Yes~intend_to_enter_any_other_Australian_film_festivals~Yes~other_Australian_film_festivals_intent_to_enter~~by_Aboriginal_filmmakers~Yes~Principal_first_name~Julia~Principal_last_name~Remmert~Principal_position~~Principal_production_company~Fremantle Arts Centre~Principal_address~1 Finnerty Street~Principal_suburb~Fremantlke~Principal_state~WA~Principal_postcode~6160~Telephone_business_hours~0894329555~Telephone_after_hours~0894329555~Principal_mobile~